        "id": 256452,
        "name": "",
        "username": "anacletus",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/858c86/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2024-12-01T16:50:52.146Z",
        "cooked": "<p>The animation is very annoying. I really don’t see why it’s necessary in the first place: Android’s unlock already has a built-in animation, so Signal’s unlock currently shows two animations. Signal is literally the only app I know that does this. Also, <strong>the iOS Signal app does not have this animation</strong>, so it feels even more arbitrary.</p>\n<p>Moreover, I believe Android provides two ways to implement (face) unlock: one that requires the user to manually tap the lock icon the face has been recognized, and one that doesn’t. The former is obviously faster and creates less friction. For some reason, Signal uses the latter, while most apps I use (including WhatsApp) use the former.</p>\n<p>Overall, Signal is probably the slowest app I know to unlock with biometrics.</p>\n<p>This issue adds to the fact that (unlike WhatsApp), Signal does not <a href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/t/show-message-content-in-notification-while-having-app-lock-enabled/21156\">show message content in notification while having app lock enabled</a>. This means that I have to continuously unlock Signal throughout the day just to read notifications (which feels even more annoying since I have a smartwatch, whose main purpose is precisely to avoid reaching out to the phone to read incoming messages). WhatsApp has an option to show/hide notifications when locked.</p>\n<p>Taken together this means that: (1) I need to manually unlock Signal much more often than other apps; and (2) every time I do it there is significant friction.</p>\n<p>Please just disable the notification!</p>",
